{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17601367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17601367"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:14:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:14:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15654"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.32,0.32,0.05,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8345"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71032"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8345"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56503"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2994"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5295"},{"type":"tags","id":"5885"},{"type":"tags","id":"7010"},{"type":"tags","id":"10111"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20127"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71032"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis maintains cortisol homeostasis through complex feedback mechanisms. Various pathological processes can disrupt this system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a condition characterised by bilateral adrenal hyperplasia and markedly elevated ACTH levels that do not suppress with dexamethasone?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal cortical adenoma","Pituitary ACTH-secreting adenoma","Ectopic ACTH-secreting tumour","Long-term prednisolone therapy","Primary bilateral adrenal hyperplasia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe key features of an \u003Cstrong\u003Eectopic ACTH-secreting tumour\u003C/strong\u003E are very high ACTH levels that do not suppress with dexamethasone, and bilateral adrenal hyperplasia due to chronic ACTH stimulation. These tumours typically produce much higher ACTH levels than pituitary sources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other conditions can be distinguished by their hormonal patterns:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal cortical adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E produces cortisol autonomously, suppressing ACTH production\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPituitary ACTH-secreting adenoma\u003C/strong\u003E (Cushing disease) shows moderately elevated ACTH that typically suppresses with high-dose dexamethasone\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong-term prednisolone therapy\u003C/strong\u003E suppresses endogenous ACTH production through negative feedback, leading to adrenal atrophy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary bilateral adrenal hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E may be ACTH-dependent or independent but usually demonstrates some degree of feedback regulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these patterns is crucial for differentiating between various causes of Cushing syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Paraneoplastic ACTH-secreting tumours cause bilateral adrenal hyperplasia and elevated ACTH levels that are not suppressible with dexamethasone.","Different causes of Cushing syndrome can be distinguished by their patterns of ACTH levels and response to dexamethasone suppression.","Ectopic ACTH production typically results in higher ACTH levels than those seen in Cushing disease."],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Clark, O. H., Duh, Q. Y., Kebebew, E., Gosnell, J. E., \u0026 Shen, W. T. (Eds.). (2016). Textbook of endocrine surgery. JP Medical Ltd","Young, W. F. (2011). Netter\u0027s Endocrine System: Netter Collection of Medical Illustrations: Endocrine System E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA","Lotfi CFP, Kremer JL, Dos Santos Passaia B, Cavalcante IP. The human adrenal cortex: growth control and disorders. Clinics (Sao Paulo). 2018 Sep 6;73(suppl 1):e473s. doi: 10.6061/clinics/2018/e473s. PMID: 30208164; PMCID: PMC6113920"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56503"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15654"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56503"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T19:05:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T19:06:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8345"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71032"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Scie